shared_text:
NMAAHC.SI.EDU
National Museum of African American History and Culture Releases ‚ÄúTalking About Race‚Äù Web Portal

Adam Titter is with Erin Titter.
June 1 at 10:10 AM ¬∑

My Local History class was so fortunate to talk to Dr. Spencer Crew less than two weeks ago. Please use these resources to talk with your kids about race.

‚ÄúSince opening the museum, the number one question we are asked is how to talk about race, especially with children. We recognize how difficult it is to start that conversation. But in a nation still struggling with the legacies of slavery, Jim Crow laws, and white supremacy, we must have these tough conversations if we have any hope of turning the page and healing. This new portal is a step in that direction.‚Äù

- Dr. Spencer Crew, interim director of the National Museum of African American History and Culture

shared_text:
Hans Herr Elementary School
March 30 at 9:51 AM ¬∑

HH Families,

The HH At Home Learning Courses are up and running! Blackboard e-mails were sent out with the course codes this morning. Teachers will also be sending the course codes home via SeeSaw. If you have not received the needed course codes, please contact me at jeffrey_smecker@L-Spioneers.org.

Our goal this week is to get as many students enrolled in the courses as possible and start getting them acclimated to the online learning environment. While we certainly wish we were doing all of this under a better set of circumstances, we are optimistic about overcoming the challenges we face while continuing to support your child's education. Our staff is collaborating virtually every day to create a positive and supportive online learning environment.

To accomplish this, we will be using Schoology as our central resource. Schoology will serve as the main hub for students to access a variety of resources your children will be using during the closure. More information will be out later this week regarding access to devices.

Be well and be safe,

-Dr. Smecker

Today is Activity Thursday with Maya. Share with us your favorite outdoor/indoor activities.

üêæHello Everyone! I can not wait for you to share what you have been doing. I have been spending a lot of time outside with my family going on long walks. I miss all of you and can‚Äôt wait to see you when we get back.

Here are a few fun facts about me.

*I am 5 years old.
*My birthday is Oct 17.
*I was part of the great thinkers dog litter.
*I was the first SSD dog place at L-S.
*I live with my cousin Shepard and my 2 human siblings.
*I love to go to work everyday, and when I come home I enjoy some quiet time under my human‚Äôs bed.
*I love neighborhood walks, and long hikes in the woods.
*Most of all, I love people (especially dog people).

Can‚Äôt wait to see what you are all doing.

~SSD Maya~

post_text: Lampeter Elementary students took a ride on The Super Dooper Bully Looper today and had fun while learning tips on how to deal with bullies. The show was one of four new Imagination Station productions from the Dutch Apple Dinner Theatre. Veteran children's theater actor (and L-S parent) Randall Frizado created the program as a positive way to address topics like bullying, self-esteem, cyber awareness, and hygiene with elementary school audiences, developing emotional learning skills along the way.

We're looking for an Application Support Specialist

Full-time, 12-month, salary exempt position available immediately. Seeking a customer service-oriented systems and data specialist to manage, support, and configure District software systems, with an emphasis on PowerSchool SIS. Successful candidate will be required to provide training and support to a diverse group of users for all applications. Associate‚Äôs Degree in a technology application field and experience is preferred, but interpersonal skills and an aptitude for quickly learning software and workflow are most important. Salary starts at $53k, commensurate with experience. Interested candidates should apply at https://tinyurl.com/so6anzy.

Deadline for applications is February 23, 2020.
